I am looking into this one. 

### Sequence of action as follows: 

1. **HandleEvent** 
2. **me.update**
3. **trigger callbacks** [0] 

[0] : https://github.com/chartjs/Chart.js/blob/master/src/core/core.tooltip.js#L508-L512

## Possible Solution: 

What I was thinking was to add a var `_activeIndex` to keep track of the index of data of first active Element. Then trigger callback depending on its state (changed or unchanged). 

I assumed if first active Element index (`chartInstance._active[0]._index`) has changed then all other active Elements has changed as well (for example, multi dataset charts). I believe the tooltip active element is obtained via nearest proximity. 


**Sample:**

```javascript 
/**
 * Helper method to determine whether activeElement data has changed
 */
function activeIndexChanged(chartInstance) {
    var predicate = true;
    /* update title by default, unless activeIndex are the same  */
    if ((chartInstance._activeIndex === chartInstance._active[0]._index)) {
        predicate = false;
    }

    // Update the activeIndex for next Check
    chartInstance._activeIndex = chartInstance._active[0]._index;

    return predicate;
}

...


/** example usage */

if (activeIndexChanged(me)) {
    model.title = me.getTitle(tooltipItems, data); 
} 
```
The other callbacks (**afterBody**, **beforeTitle**...) will need to this check as well.

@simonbrunel, @etimberg please let me know if theres any concerns with this possible solution. thanks!

What about skipping the update() if `active` items are the same as last ones?

At [core.tooltip.js#L784](https://github.com/chartjs/Chart.js/blob/312773ba7b7e2acf6cd1273c92017d3c197a992b/src/core/core.tooltip.js#L784)

```javascript
handleEvent: function(e) {

    // ...

    // Remember Last Actives
    changed = !helpers.arrayEquals(me._active, me._lastActive);
    if (!changed) {
        return false;
    }

    me._lastActive = me._active;

    // ...

}
```
